         <provenance type="found" notAfter="1911">
            <ab>This piece was found by <persName type="explorer">V. Rougier</persName> at <placeName type="modern" ref="cic-geo:duong-mong">Dưỡng Mông</placeName> before 1911, when it entered the EFEO Museum in Hanoi. There is uncertainty about the correct spelling of the place name. The French publications spell Dương-mong, but according to Trần Kỳ Phương, the correct spelling should be Dưỡng Mông, and Federico Barocco has confirmed that this is found on an American map.</ab>
            <!-- 1:250.000 map prepared on 1972 by the Defense Mapping Agency Hydrographic/Topographic Center, Washington D.C., in cooperation with the National Geographic Directorate of Vietnam.  Đưỡng Mông belong to Xã Quế Xuân , Huyện Quế Sơn , tỉnh Quảng Nam. -->
         </provenance>
         <provenance type="observed" notBefore="1915">
            <ab>Its inventory number <ptr target="#inv-efeo-hanoi"/> at the Museum was published in <bibl><ptr target="cic-bibl:finot-1915a"/>: <biblScope>18</biblScope></bibl>;
               whence, in the inventory of Campā inscriptions published in 1923, this local number was included under the entry <ptr target="#inv-general"/> (<ptr
                  target="cic-bibl:coedes-1923"/>).</ab>
         </provenance>
         <provenance type="observed" notBefore="2009">
            <ab>We identified the stone in the Bảo Tàng Lịch Sử Việt Nam (National Museum of Vietnamese History) at Hanoi in 2009 and following years, as the one bearing inventory number <ptr target="#inv-btls-qg"/>. The Museum assumed the new name Bảo Tàng Lịch Sử Quốc Gia (National Museum of History) in 2011, but this did not entail a change in the inventory number.</ab>
         </provenance>
      </history>
